default3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAlthough in practice the system of checks and balances is akin to systems respecting a more formal separation of powers, Britain’s mixed model of government firmly subordinate
defaultd
default 
defaultthe jud
defaulticiary
default to the elected branches of government. The constitutional hierarchy, which stems from the doctrine of parliamentary sovereignty
default,
default conceive
defaultd of
default the courts as 
default‘modest underworkers’ and ‘handmaids to Parliament’s will’.
default 
defaultCourts were
default to interpret the tex
defaultt and to declare the law
default,
default and they enjoyed only limited review powers over delegated authority by Parliament to subordinate bodies.
default 
default&#xa0;
default4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBy adhering to
default plain meaning (literalist/formalist) approaches to statutory interpretation (which 
defaultavoid 
defaultthe 
defaultcharge 
defaultthat 
defaultthe judiciary might 
defaultsubstitut
defaulte
default its 
defaultown 
defaultview of the law for that expressed by Parliamen
defaultt),
default 
defaultthe judiciary acknowledge that democracy and public policy (i.e. most of effective law-making) 
defaultare
default 
defaultgenerally regarded as political matters to be determined in and by
default the legislature
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe impact 
defaultof 
defaultthis
default 
defaultsubordination 
defaulton the constitutional status of the courts 
defaulthas been
default enormous. Between 1842 and the UK’s accession to the European Community in January 1973, not a single case reached the House of Lords on the question 
defaultof the absence of limitations of Parliament’s ultimate law-making authority.
default The period 
defaultfrom World War II until the 1960s ‘marked the depths of the irrelevance of the courts in the development of the constitution
default.
default’
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultB: 
defaultThe Development of Powers of 
defaultQuasi-Constitutional Review:
default&#xa0;
default6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDevelopments since the latter 
defaultdecades 
defaultof the twentieth century have prompted a re-evaluation of the constitutional position of the judiciary as necessarily 
defaultsubservient. 
defaultOver this period
default, and 
defaultas a cumulative result of the statu
defaulttory
default 
defaultconferral and arrogation of powers
default,
default 
defaultthe apex court gradually developed a ‘pronounced public law profile’
default such that the United Kingdom Supreme Court 
default(UKSC) 
defaultcan now be seen to 
defaultdischarge ‘some of the functions of a constitutional court’
default.
default In the absence
default of a documentary constitution, and in the light of the fact that the sovereignty of Parliament remains of fundamental importance to our understandings of the constitution, it is appropriate to classify these powers of review as quasi-constitutional. 
default&#xa0;
default7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe 
defaultidentif
defaulty
default two types of powers of quasi-constitutional review. The first type, explicit powers, derives from statute.
default  
defaultThe 
defaultUKSC
default 
defaulthas been allocated powers of quasi-constitutional review under the European Communities Act 1972
default (ECA)
default, the Human Rights Act 1998
default 
default(HRA)
default, and the UK
default’
defaults devolution legislation. 
default&#xa0;
default8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn the context of EU law, Parliament’s competence is substantively limited in two ways: first, it may not legislate contrary to EU law (s.2(4) EC
defaultA
default 1972); and second, courts enjoy power to ‘disapply’ national la
defaultw to the extent that it is inconsistent with directly effective provisions of EU law.
default It is acting in this capacity that the 
defaultUKSC
default 
defaultmost clearly discharges functions akin to
default the
default strong form
default 
defaultjudicial review
default exercised by Supreme and Constitutional Courts else
defaultwhere
default.  
default&#xa0;
default9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHRA
default review gives rise to consequences of a slightly different order
default,
default 
defaultpermitting
default courts to interpret primary legislation in order to achieve compliance with the Convention Rights so far as it is possible to do so
default (s.3(1) HRA)
default,
default or in the alternative providing for the issue of a declaration of incompatibility
default (s.4 HRA)
default.
default 
defaultThough neither option permits the court to mount a direct challenge to the legality of an Act of Parliament, the 
defaultHRA
default nonetheless empowers the 
defaultcourts
default 
defaultto
default test prima
defaultry legislation
default,
default whenever enacted
default,
default for compliance with human rights standards
default&#xa0;
default10.
default&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthe 
defaultcourts
default 
defaultalso 
defaultexercise power
default to determine legal disputes relating to ‘devolution issues’ 
defaultarising 
defaultout of the 
defaulttransfer of legal powers to 
defaultdevolved bodies
default.
default The power of the 
defaultUKSC
default 
default– previously exercised by the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council – is something of a departure from the traditional distinction placed by the constitution on the review of executive and legislative action, in the devolved context potentially subjectin
defaultg 
defaultboth
default to judicial review. 
default 
default&#xa0;
default11.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSovereignty-respecting measures are evident in both the 
defaultHRA 
defaultand in the devolution legislation. The 
defaultHRA 
defaultstipulates that neither the interpretation of legislation under s.3(1) nor the issue of a declaration of incompatibility un
defaultder s.4 will affect the ‘validity, continuing operation or enforcement’ of the legislative provision(s) under review. The scheme of the devolution legislation, meanwhile, subjects only devolved legislation to potential review, and contains measures designe
defaultd to preserve the sovereignty of the Westminster Parliament.
default 
default&#xa0;
default12.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn addition to those powers of quasi-constitutional review allocated by statute, the expansion of the judicial review jurisdiction (and thereby of the constitutional powers of the courts exist
defaultent at common law) has seen the development of implied powers of quasi-constitutional review by the judges themselves.  At the most straightforward level, 
defaulta judicial belief in the 
default‘
defaultsanctity
default’
default of statutory language has yielded ground to more generous and purposive techni
defaultques of construction
default.
default  Rather more fundamentally, the development of ideas associated with the ‘common law constitution’
default – including t
defaulthe 
defaultincremental 
defaultdevelopment of a body of ‘
defaultconstitutional rights’
default 
defaultand the 
defaultacknowledge
defaultment of a distinction 
defaultbetween constitutional
default and non-constitutional
default 
defaultstatutes
default – 
defaulthave
default 
defaultexposed the traditional positivist and sovereignty-driven explanation of the constitution as being 
defaultinadequate.
default The effects of th
defaultis transition, which 
defaultsaw common law standards
default (as opposed to the inferred intent of Parliament) as underpinning the courts’ regulatory function
default,
default have been described as ‘one of the most fundamental realignments of the constitutional order since the end of 
defaultthe seventeenth century’.
default  
default&#xa0;
default13.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe high watermark of this line of 
defaultcommon law 
defaultreasoning
default remains
default Lord Hoffmann
default’s articulation of the ‘principle of legality’
default in 
defaultR
default v. 
defaultSecretary of State for the Home Department, ex parte Simms
default.
default  Via the controlling mechanism of
default the common law, Hoffmann addresses one of the most controversial and divisive issues in contemporary public law discourse; the tension between the legal controls imposed by the rule of law and the theoretically limitless legal power
default of
default Parliament.  On the
default one hand,
default 
defaultHoffmann is at pains to preserve the ability of Parliament to legislate contrary to fundamental individual rights.  On the other, 
defaulthe asserts that 
defaultthe constitutional function of the common law has 
defaultexpanded 
defaultso as to 
defaultsubject primary legislation to 
defaulta degree of legal control.
default&#xa0;
default14.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWe conclude 
defaultthat in certain clearly-
defaultdefined areas of law, the UKSC 
defaultalready
default acts as a constitutional organ. It exercises quasi-constitutional powers in relation to the European Union and 
defaultunder 
defaultthe 
defaultHRA
default 
defaulta
defaultnd acts as a quasi-federal court in 
defaultdevolution cases. Hoffmann notes in 
defaultSimms
default that the apex court in the UK is empowered to ‘
defaultapply principles of constitutionality little different from those which exist in countries where the power of the legislature is 
defaultexpressly limited by a constitutional document
default.’
default This, however, overstates the point in relation to cases that fall outside the above areas of law.  Clear legislative 
defaultintent remains 
defaultof 
defaultunquestionable 
defaultauthority
default. The most the common law empowerment allows t
defaulthe judges to do is to require express or unambiguous words where Parliament wishes to override fundamental rights or the rule of law.
default&#xa0;
defaultC: 
defaultThe power of review in constitutional cases
default&#xa0;
default15.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThat t
defaulthe rule of law is one of the twin fundamentals on which the consti
defaulttution rests
default,
default 
defaultis acknowledged by scholars
default,
default 
defaultjudges
default and primary legislation
default and the sense that it is the role of the court to vindicate the rule of law has animated the incremental expansion of the judicial role since the mid-twentieth century.
default  Yet, as
default Hoffmann’s analysis reveals, it is the supremacy of Parliament that ranks first among these supposed equals. 
default&#xa0;
default16.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAny future determination of the respective constitutional role and function of the judiciary must then seek to address the tension between the s
defaultovereignty of 
defaultParliament and the rule of law
default by approaching them as equals
default.  
defaultA further formalisation of the relationship between Parliament and courts should examine how to make good the constitutional commitment to both democratic government and the rule of law.  
default&#xa0;
default17.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWe argue that the development of the constitutional function of th
defaulte courts has rendered the 
defaulttraditional
default understanding of the 
defaultnecessarily 
defaultsubordinate role of the courts obsolete. Unquestioning acceptance by the courts of legislative direction – however Draconian – may no longer be taken for granted under this new constitu
defaulttional equilibrium
default:
default the ‘respect to be shown to the considered judgment of a democratic assembly’ is no longer a matter of assumption and ‘will vary according to the subject matter and the circumstances.’
default Equally, however, the argument that the 
defaultUKSC 
defaultshoul
defaultd extend its brief and assert the ability to strike down legislation would be a clear usurpation of the powers of the legislature.  
default&#xa0;
default18.
default&#xa0; 
defaultPossible judicial responses to Parliament doing the ‘unthinkable’
default 
default– for instance, passing legislation that disenfranchise
defaultd a substantial proportion of the population on arbitrary grounds
default or insulated vast tranches of governmental activity from the scrutiny of the courts
default – 
defaulttend to be couched in 
defaultabstract 
defaultterms and are
default often
default countered with a straightforward re-assertion of 
defaultth
defaulte sovereignty of Parliament.
default 
defaultWe argue that there are three legitimate judicial responses in constitutional cases, each occupying a position between uncritical, literal application of parliamentary intent and judicial enforcement of a substantive rule of l
defaultaw.  
default&#xa0;
default19.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe most robust course available to the court draws inspiration from the seminal decision in 
defaultAnisminic
default v. 
defaultForeign Compensation Commission
default.
default  In the exceptional case of a clash between constitutional fundamentals, the 
defaultAnisminic
default decision might be depl
defaultoyed in order to support the reinstatement of a jurisdiction apparently ousted by statute, or – read more broadly – prevent the attempted insulation by statute of otherwise 
defaultultra
default 
defaultvires
default activity from judicial review.  While falling short of US-style constit
defaultutional review, the possibility of this form of judicial disobedience to primary legislation remains the most potent weapon available to the UKSC in the event of a fundamental constitutional clash. 
default&#xa0;
default20.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSitting below outright disobedience, in legal terms at l
defaulteast, would be the judicial articulation of a ‘declaration of unconstitutionality.’  Drawing inspiration from declarations of incompatibility under the HRA 1998, David Jenkins has argued that the courts possess the inherent power to declare Acts of Parliam
defaultent to be unconstitutional ‘when Parliament legislates against legal norms or fundamental baselines for political behaviour deemed by courts of special significance within Britain’s unwritten constitution.’
default Such declarations, Jenkins argues, would respect
defaultful of sovereignty in two ways.  First, they would be ‘nonbinding and not affect the legal validity’ of the statute in respect of which they were made.
default  Second, ‘the declaration openly recognizes Parliament’s exercise of sovereign power within (or, one mi
defaultght say, against) an accepted constitutional context.’
default&#xa0;
default21.
default&#xa0; 
defaultJudicial disobedience would pose the most obvious threat to Parliament’s authority by rendering subsequent applications of the legislation contingent on the court’s disobedient response (though legis
defaultlative restoration, or refinement, of the disputed provision would remain a possibility). The consequences of the issue of a ‘declaration of unconstitutionality’ would not be so severe.  A legislative response to such a declaration might result from the po
defaultlitical damage caused by the interpretative authority attached to the judicial reading of the requirements of the 
defaultconstitution, but would not be an inevitability.  The impugned statute would remain operable.  The declaration of unconstitutionality would, t
defaultherefore, better straddle the principle of judicial control and the principle of legislative supremacy, and offer greater respect to the political underpinnings of the UK constitution. 
default&#xa0;
default22.
default&#xa0; 
defaultFinally, the courts may in certain constitutional cases need to softe
defaultn the letter of the law in order to achieve fairness in individual cases
default and to vindicate the judicial presumption that 
defaultParliament legislates ‘for a European liberal democracy’ in compliance with fundamental principles
default.
default Like equity, which ‘mitigates the r
defaultigour of the common law’,
default the rule of law ensures that 
defaultthe formal legal doctrine of 
defaultParliamentary sovereignty does not lose sight of constitutional principles that are of fundamental importance in individual circumstances. 
default&#xa0;
default23.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe rule of law requires court
defaults to interpret an Act of Parliament 
defaultwhile
default ensur
defaulting
default that its application does not result in unfairness in speciﬁc cases. Attempts to reconcile parliamentary intent with the requirements of the rule of law are a less dramatic and a more realistic and workabl
defaulte suggestion than the conferral of a general discretion on the courts to disapply unconstitutional and pernicious 
defaultlegislation
default. 
default&#xa0;
default24.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe courts share in the task of policing the boundaries of a rights-based democracy with the legislature and executive
default;
default 
defaulttheir role is complementary to that of Parliament, and of the executive. 
default 
defaultTo classify
default the
default quasi-
defaultconstitutional function
defaults
default of the 
defaultcourts 
defaultas a step towards judicial supremacism is to deny the distinctive functions of the legislative and judicial branches: ‘[c
default]
defaultourts do not substitute Parliament in the making of policy decisions as they are limited by the principle of institutional integrity: “[t]here is a Rubicon which they may not cross.”’
default It also denies the crucial constitutional role of the courts in their 
defaulthabitual recognition of Parliament as sovereign.
default The constitutional functions and authority of the courts, therefore, form the embodiment of the balanced constitution in its modern incarnation.  
